Describe the property of sin and cos functions. List the properties one by one.
assistant
The sine and cosine functions are both periodic functions, meaning they repeat their values at regular intervals. The period of the sine and cosine functions is 2π radians (or 360 degrees), which means that the values of the sine and cosine functions repeat themselves every 2π radians.

The sine function is a continuous and increasing function, meaning that as the input (x) increases, the output (y) also increases. The cosine function is also a continuous and increasing function, but it starts from a negative value and decreases as x increases.

The sine function has a maximum value of 1 and a minimum value of -1. The cosine function has a maximum value of 1 and a minimum value of -1.

The sine and cosine functions are related to the unit circle, which is a circle with a radius of 1 centered at the origin of the coordinate plane. The sine and cosine functions are the y and x coordinates, respectively, of the point on the unit circle that corresponds to a given angle x.

The sine and cosine functions are used to model various phenomena, such as the motion of objects in the universe, the behavior of waves, and the behavior of light. They are also used in calculus and other areas of mathematics.


